<section id="research">
  <hr class="section-rule" />
  <p class="label">01 — research</p>
  <h2>What I'm thinking about</h2>
  
  <div class="content">
    <div class="interest">
      <h3>Model Robustness</h3>
      <p>I'm interested in how models fail once the real world stops matching their training data — including small, deliberate changes to an input designed to fool them. Most benchmarks are too forgiving about this. I want to understand what it actually takes to keep a model reliable once those comfortable assumptions break down.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="interest">
      <h3>Adversarial ML</h3>
      <p>Defenses that look strong in a paper often fall apart the moment someone actually tries to break the system. I study which weaknesses genuinely matter once a model is in production, and why the metrics we use to grade "security" often miss the ways systems actually get exploited.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="interest">
      <h3>Multimodal Systems</h3>
      <p>Getting a model to connect what it sees with what it reads is rarely as clean as it looks in a demo. I explore different ways of combining vision and language, especially when compute is limited and being fast matters as much as being right.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="interest">
      <h3>ML in High-Noise Environments</h3>
      <p>Financial markets are one of the hardest places to apply ML — the useful signal is tiny compared to the noise, the patterns keep shifting, and overfitting doesn't show up until it's already cost real money. Building and testing trading signals at WorldQuant has changed how I think about making a model generalize when there's no clean benchmark to check it against.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

